-- NODE 17: The Privatization Playbook Pattern
(
  'The Pattern — The Privatization Playbook',
  'pattern-privatization-playbook',
  'The playbook never changes: Defund → Declare Failure → Privatize → Profit. Congress forced the Post Office to prepay 75 years of retiree benefits — a requirement imposed on no other institution — then pointed to "losses" as proof government doesn''t work. 87% of USPS losses come from that artificial mandate.',
  E'# The Privatization Playbook Pattern (1980s–Present)\n\n## Summary\nThe playbook never changes. Step 1: defund the public institution. Step 2: point to declining performance as evidence "government doesn''t work." Step 3: propose private-sector "solution." Step 4: profit. The formula has been applied to education, water, prisons, housing, healthcare, postal service, transportation. The result is always the same: a public good becomes a private revenue stream, costs increase, quality decreases, poorest communities bear heaviest burden.\n\n## The Pattern Matrix\n\n**Public Education**\n• Defund: Per-pupil cuts; unfunded mandates\n• "Failure": "Failing public schools"\n• Privatization: Charter schools, vouchers\n• Who Profits: Charter mgmt orgs; DeVos family invested $200M+ in school choice\n\n**U.S. Postal Service**\n• Defund: 2006 Act forced $72B prefunding of 75 years retiree benefits — no other agency faces this\n• "Failure": "USPS is bankrupt"\n• Privatization: FedEx, UPS capture market\n• Who Profits: 87% of USPS reported losses directly caused by artificial prefunding mandate\n\n**Public Water**\n• Defund: Infrastructure investment deferred decades\n• "Failure": "Government can''t maintain water systems"\n• Privatization: Bechtel, Nestlé, Veolia, Suez\n• Who Profits: Bechtel raised Cochabamba rates 200%; Nestlé pays $200/year for 576K gal/day\n\n**Public Prisons**\n• Defund: Mandatory minimums, three-strikes laws\n• "Failure": "Overcrowded, dangerous facilities"\n• Privatization: CoreCivic, GEO Group\n• Who Profits: $1B+ each in ICE contracts (2025); execs donated $1M+ to Trump PACs\n\n**Public Housing**\n• Defund: HUD funding cuts; HOPE VI demolitions\n• "Failure": "Projects are dangerous"\n• Privatization: BlackRock, Invitation Homes\n• Who Profits: Invitation Homes: 80,000+ rentals; rents up 30%+ in many markets\n\n**NHS (UK)**\n• Defund: Funding frozen below inflation for years\n• "Failure": "NHS waiting times prove public healthcare fails"\n• Privatization: Private contractors 25% of NHS revenue after 2013 Act\n• Who Profits: Virgin Care, Serco, private hospital chains\n\n**Social Security**\n• Defund: Tax cap frozen; trust fund borrowing\n• "Failure": "Social Security is going bankrupt"\n• Privatization: Proposed private accounts (Bush 2005)\n• Who Profits: Wall Street estimated $940B in management fees from privatized accounts\n\n## The Red Pill\nCongress forced Post Office to prepay 75 years of retiree benefits — requirement imposed on no other institution — then pointed to "losses" as proof government doesn''t work. 87% of USPS losses come from that artificial mandate. Same pattern everywhere: defund public schools, claim they failed, hand contracts to charter companies funded by donors who lobbied for cuts. Privatize water, charge 200% more. Privatize prisons, lobby for longer sentences. The playbook isn''t hidden — it''s documented in lobbying records, campaign finance filings, profit margins of every company feeding on corpse of public institution.\n\n## Sources\nGAO. "Postal Accountability Act: Financial Impact Assessment." 2019.\nOpenSecrets. "Private Prison Company Political Spending." 2024.\nNational Housing Law Project. "HOPE VI: Public Housing Demolition." 2002.\nNHS Support Federation. "NHS Privatisation: The Evidence." 2023.',
  'Pattern Analysis / Meta-Item',
  '1980-01-01',
  'verified',
  jsonb_build_object('category', 'Cross-Pillar Pattern', 'pillar', 'Cross-Pillar Pattern', 'years', '1980s–Present', 'importance', 'PURE_GOLD', 'tags', ARRAY['privatization', 'pattern analysis', 'public services', 'neoliberalism'], 'connection_web', ARRAY['Corporate Consolidation', 'Water Privatization', 'Prison Industrial Complex', 'Student Loan Crisis'])
),

-- NODE 18: The Health-to-Profit Conversion Pattern
(
  'The Pattern — The Health-to-Profit Conversion',
  'pattern-health-to-profit-conversion',
  'The formula is industrial. A company discovers its product causes harm. It commissions studies confirming harm. It buries the studies. It funds research to create doubt. It continues selling for decades. When undeniable, it settles, admits no wrongdoing, pays a fraction of profits. No executive goes to prison. The cycle repeats.',
  E'# The Health-to-Profit Conversion Pattern (1950s–Present)\n\n## Summary\nThe formula is industrial. A company discovers its product causes harm. It commissions internal studies that confirm the harm. It buries the studies. It funds external research designed to create doubt. It continues selling the product for as long as possible — sometimes decades. When evidence becomes undeniable, it negotiates a settlement, admits no wrongdoing, and pays a fine representing a fraction of profits generated during suppression period. No executive goes to prison. The company continues operating. The cycle repeats.\n\nThis is the documented, exposed, litigated business model of tobacco, opioid manufacturers, Merck, 3M, DuPont, Dow Chemical, Standard Oil, Johns Manville, Monsanto across seven decades. The evidence comes from their own internal documents — discovered during litigation.\n\n## The Pattern Matrix\n\n**Tobacco (Philip Morris, RJR, etc.)**\n• When They Knew: 1950s — internal research confirmed cancer link\n• How Long Suppressed: 40+ years\n• Revenue During Suppression: Hundreds of billions\n• Settlement/Fines: $206 billion (1998 Master Settlement)\n• Criminal Accountability: Zero prosecutions\n\n**OxyContin (Purdue Pharma / Sacklers)**\n• When They Knew: 1999 — internal reports showed addiction risk\n• How Long Suppressed: 20+ years\n• Revenue During Suppression: $35B OxyContin revenue; $4B withdrawn by Sacklers\n• Settlement/Fines: $15+ billion\n• Criminal Accountability: Zero Sackler family members charged\n\n**Vioxx (Merck)**\n• When They Knew: 1997–2000 — internal studies showed cardiac risk\n• How Long Suppressed: 4+ years on market\n• Revenue During Suppression: $2.5B/year peak sales\n• Settlement/Fines: $6.6+ billion\n• Criminal Accountability: One corporate misdemeanor; ~38,000 excess deaths\n\n**PFAS (3M, DuPont)**\n• When They Knew: 1960s — 3M internal toxicology studies\n• How Long Suppressed: 50+ years\n• Revenue During Suppression: Tens of billions\n• Settlement/Fines: $10.3B (3M) + $1.18B (DuPont/Chemours)\n• Criminal Accountability: Zero charges\n\n**Leaded Gasoline (Ethyl Corp/Standard Oil)**\n• When They Knew: 1922 — workers at production facilities died\n• How Long Suppressed: 68 years (until 1990 ban)\n• Revenue During Suppression: Incalculable\n• Settlement/Fines: No significant settlement\n• Criminal Accountability: Zero; 68M children with toxic blood lead levels\n\n**Asbestos (Johns Manville et al.)**\n• When They Knew: 1930s — industry health studies confirmed lung disease\n• How Long Suppressed: 40+ years\n• Revenue During Suppression: Billions\n• Settlement/Fines: Bankruptcy trusts totaling $30+ billion\n• Criminal Accountability: Zero convictions; Johns Manville exec memo (1966): "if you have enjoyed a good life... why not die from it?"\n\n**Roundup/Glyphosate (Monsanto/Bayer)**\n• When They Knew: Internal "Monsanto Papers" showed knowledge of cancer risk\n• How Long Suppressed: Ongoing\n• Revenue During Suppression: Billions annually\n• Settlement/Fines: $18+ billion (ongoing)\n• Criminal Accountability: Zero charges\n\n**DES (multiple pharma cos.)**\n• When They Knew: 1953 — clinical trial showed ineffective for preventing miscarriage\n• How Long Suppressed: 18–25 years continued prescribing\n• Revenue During Suppression: Unknown\n• Settlement/Fines: Litigation ongoing decades later\n• Criminal Accountability: Zero; 2M+ daughters exposed to carcinogen\n\n**Thalidomide (Grünenthal)**\n• When They Knew: Pre-market — inadequate testing\n• How Long Suppressed: Marketed 1957–1962\n• Revenue During Suppression: Unknown\n• Settlement/Fines: Grünenthal fund €50M (2012)\n• Criminal Accountability: Zero convictions; 8,000+ children born without limbs; apology 50 years later\n\n## The Red Pill\nThey all knew. Every single one. Tobacco knew in the 1950s and suppressed for 40 years. Purdue knew about OxyContin addiction in 1999 and extracted $4B while 500,000 Americans died. 3M knew about PFAS toxicity in the 1960s and suppressed for half a century. Merck knew Vioxx caused heart attacks and kept selling until 38,000 people died. Leaded gasoline industry knew in 1922 — when workers started dying — and kept lead in gas for 68 years, poisoning 68M children. An asbestos exec wrote in 1966: "if you have enjoyed a good life while working with asbestos products, why not die from it?" The settlements are always in billions. Criminal prosecutions are always zero. The pattern is not a failure of regulation — it is the business model itself. Discover harm. Suppress data. Maximize profit. Settle for a fraction. Repeat.\n\n## Sources\nMichaels, David. Doubt Is Their Product: How Industry''s Assault on Science Threatens Your Health. Oxford University Press, 2008.\nNew York State AG. "Sackler Family Withdrawals from Purdue Pharma." 2019.\nDOJ. "PFAS Contamination: 3M Settlement." 2023.\nNAAG. "Master Settlement Agreement." 1998.\nProctor, Robert N. Golden Holocaust: Origins of the Cigarette Catastrophe. UC Press, 2011.',
  'Pattern Analysis / Meta-Item',
  '1950-01-01',
  'verified',
  jsonb_build_object('category', 'Cross-Pillar Pattern', 'pillar', 'Cross-Pillar Pattern', 'years', '1950s–Present', 'importance', 'PURE_GOLD', 'tags', ARRAY['corporate harm', 'pattern analysis', 'tobacco', 'opioids', 'PFAS', 'public health'], 'connection_web', ARRAY['Opioid Crisis', 'Vioxx', 'PFAS Forever Chemicals', 'Tobacco Industry', 'FDA Revolving Door'])
